  "Idea": "This paper introduces Hierarchical Information Gate Modeling (HIGM), a novel framework designed to quantify the causal contribution of Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) hierarchies to the predictability of information density fluctuations in natural text. Rather than modeling discourse structure as a latent tree to be learned from scratch, HIGM treats established RST parses as functional processing pathways that modulate local surprisal through context-dependent gating mechanisms. Each discourse unit—nucleus or satellite—is equipped with a learnable gate that dynamically attenuates or amplifies incoming information based on its rhetorical function (e.g., contrast, elaboration, background), depth in the hierarchy, and local context. These gates operate on surprisal vectors derived from frozen pretrained language models (e.g., LLaMA-3), transforming them hierarchically from leaf to root. The final output is a reconstructed surprisal contour, which is compared against ground-truth values to train the gate parameters via gradient descent. Crucially, the magnitude and variance of gate activations are used to compute a \u2018Predictive Power Index\u2019 (PPI) for each discourse relation type and depth level, offering a fine-grained, interpretable metric of structural influence. To ensure robustness across domains, we integrate an uncertainty-aware normalization module inspired by consistent decision frameworks (cf. Paper 2), which adjusts gate contributions based on parser confidence and cross-domain reliability. This allows HIGM to downweight noisy annotations in low-resource domains while preserving high-fidelity signals in well-annotated corpora. We validate the model on diverse datasets—including news articles, academic texts, and narrative fiction—and demonstrate that certain mid-level relations (e.g., concession, exemplification) exhibit disproportionately high PPI scores, supporting a refined version of the Structured Context Hypothesis. Moreover, ablation studies reveal that gate depth nonlinearity—not mere proximity to root—drives prediction accuracy, suggesting that humans may exploit hierarchical depth for cognitive load management. The framework enables new applications in adaptive text simplification, where gates can be manipulated to flatten information peaks, and in AI-generated content evaluation, where PPI serves as a diagnostic tool for rhetorical coherence. By reframing RST from a representational schema to a dynamic information control system, HIGM offers a paradigm shift in computational discourse analysis.",
