  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework—Differentiable Hierarchical Discourse Modeling (DHDM)—to investigate how the hierarchical organization of discourse units influences the predictability of information density fluctuations in natural text. Rather than relying on fixed RST trees with binary nuclearity or static weighted extensions, DHDM introduces a neural architecture that learns soft, differentiable discourse hierarchies end-to-end, jointly optimized to predict local surprisal values derived from pretrained language models. The core innovation lies in parameterizing the tree structure using continuous merge-split probabilities over text spans, inspired by unsupervised parsing methods like those in Paper 3, but extended with gradient-based optimization through Gumbel-Softmax relaxation or straight-through estimators. Each node in the latent tree is assigned a learnable weight representing its functional contribution to information modulation, conditioned on its depth, rhetorical role, and position in the global structure. These weights are then used to compute hierarchical context vectors that inform a surprisal prediction head. By training this model on large corpora of naturally occurring texts (e.g., essays, news articles, narratives), we can quantify how much variance in information density is explained by different levels of the learned hierarchy. Crucially, we analyze whether deeper nodes (e.g., clause-level satellites) exert disproportionate influence on high-surprisal events, testing the Structured Context Hypothesis with greater precision than previous approaches. The model also enables ablation studies on hierarchy depth, weight sparsity, and rhetorical function masking, offering interpretability into which structural patterns most strongly regulate information flow. This work bridges linguistic theory and deep learning by transforming RST from an annotation scheme into a dynamic, predictive mechanism. Its impact extends to text generation, w